<h3>Appearance</h3>
<p>Red Burgundy displays a characteristic <strong>pale to medium ruby color</strong> with garnet edges, reflecting Pinot Noir's naturally thin skin. Young wines show vibrant cherry-red hues, while aged examples develop brick and amber tints at the rim. The wine typically has <strong>medium viscosity</strong> with delicate legs that cling briefly to the glass—a sign of moderate alcohol (12.5-14%) and the grape's inherently lighter structure compared to Bordeaux varietals.</p>

<h3>Aromatics: The Soul of Burgundy</h3>
<p>The nose reveals Burgundy's complexity in layers. <strong>Primary fruit aromas</strong> range from bright red cherry and raspberry in Côte de Beaune wines to darker strawberry and cranberry in Côte de Nuits expressions. <strong>Secondary fermentation notes</strong> contribute subtle spice—white pepper, clove, and the distinctive "forest floor" earthiness from whole-cluster fermentation and native yeasts.</p>

<p><strong>Tertiary aging aromas</strong> develop remarkable complexity: dried roses, violets, leather, mushroom, and that quintessential Burgundian "barnyard" funk (from Brettanomyces in small amounts) that aficionados prize. Premium Burgundies often show mineral notes—wet limestone, chalk, or iron—directly reflecting their terroir.</p>

<h3>Palate and Texture</h3>
<p>Red Burgundy feels <strong>medium-bodied with high acidity</strong> that provides spine and longevity. Tannins are typically soft and integrated rather than grippy—a result of Pinot Noir's delicate skin structure and traditional Burgundian winemaking that emphasizes elegance over power. The texture is often described as "silky" or "velvety," with an almost weightless quality despite intense flavor concentration.</p>

<h3>Flavor Journey</h3>
<p>The flavor profile mirrors the aromatics but with added depth. Expect <strong>red fruit dominance</strong>—cherry, raspberry, strawberry—supported by earthy undertones of mushroom, wet leaves, and mineral salinity. Spice notes include cinnamon, allspice, and dried herbs, particularly in wines from warmer vintages or premier cru vineyards.</p>

<h3>Finish and Quality Markers</h3>
<p>Premium red Burgundy shows a <strong>long, persistent finish</strong> that can last 30-45 seconds, with flavors that evolve and deepen rather than simply fade. Quality markers include aromatic complexity, seamless integration of alcohol and acidity, and that distinctive "mineral backbone" that speaks of limestone-rich soils. The greatest Burgundies exhibit what the French call "persistence aromatique"—flavors that return in waves minutes after swallowing.</p>

  <h2>Food Pairing Guide</h2>

<p>Red Burgundy's ethereal Pinot Noir creates magical flavor bridges through its bright acidity, silky tannins, and distinctive earthy minerality. The key to successful pairings lies in complementing the wine's natural elegance rather than overwhelming its delicate fruit profile.</p>

<h3>Classic Regional Pairings</h3>
<p>Burgundian tradition offers time-tested combinations: <strong>coq au vin</strong> harmonizes the wine's cherry notes with slow-braised chicken, while <strong>beef bourguignon</strong> mirrors the wine's terroir complexity. The regional specialty of <strong>escargots de Bourgogne</strong> works beautifully with village-level wines, as the garlic-parsley butter echoes the wine's herbal undertones without masking its fruit.</p>

<h3>The Flavor Bridge Principle</h3>
<p>Red Burgundy's moderate tannins and vibrant acidity create natural bridges with foods containing similar structural elements. The wine's characteristic earthy minerality pairs exceptionally with <strong>mushroom-based dishes</strong>, particularly wild chanterelles or morels, creating an umami synergy that amplifies both components.</p>

<h3>Versatile Everyday Options</h3>
<ul class="space-y-2">
<li><strong>Duck breast with cherry gastrique</strong> - The fruit-forward nature of Côte de Beaune wines complements duck's richness</li>
<li><strong>Grilled salmon with herbs</strong> - Lighter Burgundies bridge the gap between red and white wine pairings</li>
<li><strong>Roasted pork tenderloin</strong> - The wine's acidity cuts through fat while complementing the meat's subtle sweetness</li>
<li><strong>Aged Gruyère or Époisses cheese</strong> - Regional cheeses share similar terroir characteristics</li>
</ul>

<h3>Special Occasion Selections</h3>
<p>For premier cru and grand cru bottles, consider <strong>rack of lamb with rosemary</strong>, where the herb's earthiness mirrors the wine's mineral complexity, or <strong>venison medallions</strong> that can stand up to the wine's concentrated fruit without overwhelming its finesse. The natural gaminess creates an ideal flavor bridge with aged Burgundy's secondary characteristics.</p>

<p>The wine's natural acidity also makes it surprisingly compatible with <strong>tomato-based dishes</strong> like ratatouille, proving red Burgundy's remarkable versatility at the table.</p>

