<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Village Hierarchy</strong> - Red Burgundy follows a strict appellation pyramid: Regional (Bourgogne Rouge), Village (like Gevrey-Chambertin), Premier Cru, and Grand Cru. A well-made Village wine from a top producer like Armand Rousseau often outperforms a mediocre Premier Cru. Focus on the producer's reputation first, then the vineyard classification.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Cooler Than Bordeaux</strong> - Red Burgundy's delicate Pinot Noir structure shines at 60-62°F (15-17°C), about 5 degrees cooler than full-bodied reds. Too warm and the alcohol dominates the subtle earth and fruit nuances. Place the bottle in the refrigerator for 15-20 minutes before serving if stored at room temperature.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Only When Necessary</strong> - Young red Burgundy (under 8 years) rarely needs decanting due to Pinot Noir's naturally soft tannins. However, wines from powerhouse vintages like 2005 or 2009, or age-worthy producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti, benefit from 30-45 minutes of gentle aeration to soften any tight structure and reveal complexity.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy-Specific Glassware</strong> - The ideal glass has a large, balloon-shaped bowl that narrows significantly at the rim (like Riedel's Burgundy Grand Cru glass). This shape captures Burgundy's ethereal aromatics—wet leaves, forest floor, red fruits—while concentrating them at the nose. Avoid wide-rimmed glasses that disperse these delicate scents.</li>

  <li><strong>Understand the 10-15 Year Sweet Spot</strong> - Most red Burgundy from quality producers hits peak drinking between 10-15 years after vintage. Primary fruit evolves into complex secondary notes: mushroom, truffle, leather, and game. Wines from top sites like Chambertin or La Tâche can develop for 20-30 years, but most Village and Premier Cru wines are best consumed within this golden window.</li>

  <li><strong>Read the Producer's Style</strong> - Burgundy producers fall into distinct camps: traditionalists like Henri Jayer use whole cluster fermentation and minimal new oak, creating ethereal, terroir-driven wines. Modernists like Jean-Nicolas Méo employ more destemming and new oak, producing richer, more immediately appealing styles. Know the house style before purchasing to match your preferences.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Drinking by Vintage Character</strong> - Cool vintages (2008, 2014, 2016) produce elegant, high-acid wines that need 8-12 years to soften. Warm vintages (2009, 2015, 2020) create riper, more approachable wines that can be enjoyed younger but still age beautifully. Check vintage reports to understand when your specific bottle will be at its peak.</li>

  <li><strong>Store Horizontally in Cool, Stable Conditions</strong> - Red Burgundy's delicate Pinot Noir is particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations. Ideal storage is 55°F (13°C) with 70% humidity. Even slight warming can prematurely age these wines, causing the signature bright acidity to fade and fruit to become stewed. Consistency is more important than the exact temperature.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Red Burgundy's aging potential varies dramatically by classification and vintage quality. <strong>Village-level wines</strong> typically peak within 5-8 years, while Premier Cru bottlings can develop beautifully for 10-15 years. Grand Cru Burgundies from exceptional vintages like 2005, 2010, or 2015 can age gracefully for 20-30 years or more, with legendary producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti showing remarkable longevity beyond four decades.</p>

<h3>Evolution in the Bottle</h3>

<p>Young red Burgundy displays bright red fruit—strawberry, raspberry, and cherry—alongside pronounced acidity and firm but silky tannins. As it ages, the wine undergoes remarkable transformation. Primary fruit evolves into complex secondary aromas of forest floor, dried roses, and leather. Tertiary notes emerge after 10+ years: truffle, game, tobacco, and the distinctive "barnyard" funk from Brettanomyces that many consider quintessentially Burgundian when kept in check.</p>

<p>The wine's texture becomes increasingly velvety as tannins polymerize and integrate. Acidity remains backbone but softens, allowing the wine's mineral core—that essential expression of limestone-rich terroir—to shine through.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store red Burgundy at a consistent <strong>55-57°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 70-75% humidity. Position bottles horizontally to keep corks moist. Burgundy's delicate Pinot Noir is particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations and light exposure, which can cause premature aging and loss of aromatic complexity.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Development</h3>

<p>Well-aged Burgundy shows brick-orange rim coloration while maintaining a ruby core. Aromas become more integrated and complex. <strong>Warning signs of spoilage</strong> include vinegar-like acetic acid smells, excessive volatile acidity, or complete loss of fruit character. Cork taint presents as wet cardboard aromas, while heat damage results in stewed, jammy flavors that mask Burgundy's characteristic elegance and site-specific expression.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between red Burgundy and Pinot Noir from other regions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red Burgundy is made exclusively from Pinot Noir grapes grown in Burgundy, France, but it expresses distinctive characteristics shaped by the region's limestone-rich soils and continental climate. While California or Oregon Pinot Noir tends to be fruitier and more approachable, red Burgundy typically shows more earthy minerality, higher acidity, and complex secondary aromas of forest floor, dried roses, and spices. The strict AOC regulations and centuries-old winemaking traditions also create a more restrained, terroir-driven style compared to New World expressions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is red Burgundy good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red Burgundy can be challenging for beginners due to its subtle, earthy complexity and high acidity, which differs significantly from the bold, fruit-forward wines many new drinkers prefer. However, entry-level Burgundies from appellations like Bourgogne Rouge or Côte de Beaune villages offer a gentler introduction to the style. Starting with younger vintages (3-5 years old) and pairing them with food helps beginners appreciate Burgundy's elegant, food-friendly character before progressing to more complex Premier and Grand Cru bottlings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why is red Burgundy so expensive compared to other Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red Burgundy's high prices stem from extremely limited production due to Burgundy's small vineyard plots, strict yield restrictions, and the fact that many prestigious climats are divided among multiple small growers. The region's complex appellation system means that Grand Cru vineyards like Romanée-Conti comprise just 1.8 hectares, while even village-level wines come from tiny parcels with centuries of reputation. Additionally, global demand far exceeds supply, particularly for wines from renowned producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti, Henri Jayer, or Armand Rousseau.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve red Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red Burgundy should be served slightly cooler than most red wines, ideally between 60-65°F (15-18°C), which is about 30 minutes in the refrigerator before serving. This cooler temperature preserves Pinot Noir's delicate aromatics and prevents the alcohol from overwhelming the wine's subtle fruit and earthy characteristics. Young, simpler Burgundies can be served on the cooler end, while mature Grand Crus benefit from the warmer range to fully express their complex bouquet.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age red Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The aging potential of red Burgundy varies dramatically by appellation and producer quality, with basic Bourgogne Rouge best consumed within 5-7 years, while Premier Crus can develop beautifully for 10-15 years. Grand Cru Burgundies from top producers can age gracefully for 20-30 years or more, developing complex tertiary aromas of leather, truffle, and dried fruits. However, Burgundy's aging curve is unpredictable—some wines may close down for several years before reopening, making proper cellar conditions (55°F, 70% humidity, darkness) essential for optimal development.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good alternatives to expensive red Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For similar elegance and earthiness at lower prices, consider Pinot Noir from Sancerre Rouge, which shares Burgundy's limestone soils, or wines from the Côte Chalonnaise appellations like Mercurey and Givry. German Spätburgunder from Baden or the Ahr Valley offers comparable finesse and food-friendliness, while Oregon's Willamette Valley produces Pinot Noirs with similar restraint and complexity. For the ultimate budget alternative, explore Burgundy négociant bottlings from reputable houses like Louis Jadot or Joseph Drouhin, which offer authentic regional character at more accessible prices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Côte de Nuits and Côte de Beaune red wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Côte de Nuits reds, from villages like Gevrey-Chambertin and Vosne-Romanée, tend to be more structured, powerful, and age-worthy due to iron-rich soils and eastern exposure that provides intense morning sun. Côte de Beaune reds from appellations like Volnay and Pommard are generally more approachable and elegant, with softer tannins and more immediate charm thanks to clay-limestone soils with better drainage. While both express classic Burgundian terroir, Côte de Nuits produces most of Burgundy's most prestigious and long-lived reds, while Côte de Beaune excels at food-friendly, earlier-drinking styles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant red Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young red Burgundy (under 8-10 years) rarely needs decanting since Pinot Noir is naturally low in tannins, but a brief 30-minute decant can help integrate oak and soften any harsh edges. Mature Burgundies should be handled carefully—stand the bottle upright for 24 hours before opening, then decant gently to separate sediment, serving immediately to preserve delicate aromatics. Very old or fragile Burgundies (20+ years) may lose their charm quickly once exposed to air, so taste first and decant only if necessary, preferably using a small decanter to minimize air exposure.</p>
